content:
The year was 1944. Leo, a young soldier, crouched in the frozen mud of a French hedgerow. Dawn was a grey smear. Around him, the rumble of distant guns was the world’s only heartbeat.

He clutched a worn photograph of his mother. Fear was a cold stone in his gut. Then, the whistle. The sky tore open with fire and thunder. “Go!” his sergeant roared.

Leo ran, not for glory, but for the promise of a quiet morning, for an end to the screaming metal. He ran, one man in the vast, terrible machine, toward the light of a world not yet won.
